                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The opening point of this whole thread lead to something that is interesting.  A lot of people are in it for their guild and friends in game, but it seems as soon as they hit a forum,  a fair amount of the time it just boils right down to themselves.  I know a bstlord that dislikes the fact that the bstlord pet heal is much worse than the mage pet heal.  It's gone to the extent where on raid mobs that do severe ae's, the bstlord basically have to just chain heal the pet to keep it alive, without any time for other spells (and thus without time to heal himself, so he's still as much a burden on the clerics as a mage would be, and no I'm not doing this down to the line on mathematics with mage/bstlord resists, although if I could without taking a half hour to figure that out, I would).  This cripples bstlord dps on mobs like that.  I know they aren't a dps class, but look up the latest mage pet heals compared to the bstlord ones.  On top of that, bstlords came out as the premier class to have the ability of pets that zone with you.  shortly afterwards it was taken away from the class, and then brought back as something for everyone.  While I have no problem with that as an enchanter, I'd say it definitely takes some of the icing off the cake for the class.  I guess my strongest point there is about the pet heal, but overall, I'd say that people including myself should realize that we aren't the only class out there with problems.  I've always held the view that each class  goes through cycles of uberness.  Like shamans were REALLY uber in velious/kunark era, and since then, they haven't really stood out to that extent even though I see them around a lot, and see them do well in groups and raids.  Rogues were also really amazing back in that era, then suffered a lull in PoP and maybe luclin too, and now they're back on top in my book.  Wizards back during kunark etc.. on my server could almost never get a group since ANY melee whatsoever could outdps them in the long run due to their pitiful mana regeneration and lack of efficiency, and due to the group's primary goal usuallly being to just get the most exp possible.  Back in the basic game, necromancers seemed godly to me.  Somewhere in kunark at the 50+ line they just died for a bit in that respect and now they're back as a pretty balanced class.  I know this is a weird place to put this but I"m really sorry for my lack of paragraphs and thread structure.  I'ts 6 08 am.  But, aside from wizards being so unwanted back then, I've never seen a class so unneccesary as an enchanter in a world where you don't need crowd control, and where pop style charm is obsolete I cahrmed a LOT in sebilis, and while powerful, it was not overpowering back in that time period.  The power level charm had during that era would be fine too.  
<br />

<br />

<br />
   I'm pushing enter a few times, and even space to resemble a paragraph because this is a different and effectually important part of my post.  How much should buffs count towards class balance nowadays?  I mean enchanters get the clarity line, but frankly having played one as my main for so long I see it as more of a hindrance than anything else.  I don't play eq so I can give people clarity and then when they tell me haste pls reply "ask expert he has salik, also tell him to make his title Expert Jeweler and then /surname Jeweler so that he can be Expert Jeweler Expert Jeweler."      While that is legally contributing, there's no fun in it.  Back in sebilis when that was the main grounds and some tards didn't darkness a mob and we got a train that kept going down the entire line to the Bonecaster's robe spawn from the exit and we actually killed it all due to effective use of active class abilities is where the fun of the class is at.  I remember in vex thall when me and another enchanter named Haze (he's a jerk when I was new to vt we were at a certain point and I asked if it was ok to click down he said that it was and I clicked down and there were just 3 mobs down there and they killed me and everyone laughed but me becuase I was /ooc'ing I hat eyou haze and dying)  mezzed a huge train together, and were ACTIVELY part of a  guild effort  that almost wiped us collectively as a guild but we pulled through and lived.    I can easily say that that was more fun than claritying a billion people.  I don't see any mages going "OMG IM CASTING MOD ROD SO THAT YOU CAN CLICK IT AND HAVE MANA ITS LIKE AN ADVENTURE FULL OF FUN AND EXCITEMENT!  I LOVE THIS GAME!" and then going into an even larger dialogue about their sporadic joy like in those newfangled old navy commercials.  While granted, enchanters slipped largely as a wanted buffing class for exp groups due to KEI and shaman's/bstlords having worse yet workable hastes, these buffs are still considered largely at least by soe to be one of the primary reasons to play the class.  While I woudln't advise them to make any more content like the rathe council (frankly I wanted to be replaced by a bard so I could be watching tv but my char could be  <img src="images/smiles/eusa_boohoo.gif" alt="eusa_boohoo.gif" border="0" />  <img src="images/smiles/eusa_boohoo.gif" alt="eusa_boohoo.gif" border="0" />  <img src="images/smiles/eusa_boohoo.gif" alt="eusa_boohoo.gif" border="0" />  RARR  ing with the non stop casting of their mez song) , buffing simply should not be the primary focus or ever even considered as the primary focus of the class.  Encounters like the ones that actually use mez in potime are very good examples of what I would consider proper content to use mezmerize (which I think should be the most emphasized ability as opposed to clarity and saliks)  Also, to make things well rounded, how about Over abilities, like bards get an overhaste, how about enchanters get an over slow that would slow 15% on top of ANYTHING, even negating teh partially slowed mitigations it would be like a  james bond slow that goes behind enemy lines and meets lots of promiscuous.. well anyways never mind about that but perhaps as things currently are in the game, buffs should be considered as lesser abilities in terms of class balance.  Clerics don't derive massive pleasure out of mgb'ing symbol.  Every cleric I know either complains about it or says "hey, it's part of the job".   I just ran out of Cherry Coke so I'm going to stop typing now.  Sorry you had to read this.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
